{"title_page": "Grande de Santiago River", "text_new": "{{distinguish|Rio Grande}}\n{{more footnotes|date=September 2017}}\n{{expand Spanish|R\u00edo Grande de Santiago|date=July 2012}}\n{{Infobox river\n | name              = R\u00edo Grande de Santiago\n | image             = Rio Santiago.jpg\n | image_size        = 250px\n | image_caption     = Grande de Santiago River at the [[Nayarit]]\u2013[[Jalisco]] border\n | map               = Mexico rivers.jpg\n | map_size          = 250px\n | map_caption       = Major rivers of Mexico, with Grande de Santiago (labelled Rio Santiago) in west\u2013center\n | source1_location  = [[Lake Chapala]]\n | mouth_location    = [[Pacific Ocean]] at [[San Blas, Nayarit|San Blas]] / [[Santiago Ixcuintla]], [[Nayarit]]\n | subdivision_type1 = Country\n | subdivision_name1 = [[Mexico]]\n | progression       = \n | length            = {{Convert|433|km|mi|0|abbr=on}}\n | source1_elevation = \n | mouth_elevation   = \n | mouth_coordinates = {{coord|21|37|41|N|105|26|52|W|display=inline,title}}\n | discharge1_avg    = Average: {{convert|320|m3/s|cuft/s}}<br>Maximum: {{convert|2113|m3/s|cuft/s}}<br>Minimum: {{convert|29.5|m3/s|cuft/s}}<br><ref name=\"RDD\">{{cite web|url=http://www.sage.wisc.edu/riverdata/scripts/station_table.php?qual=32&filenum=2250 |title=Santiago Discharge near El Capomal |publisher=Center for Sustainability and the Global Environment |work=River Discharge Database |date= 1965\u20131981 |accessdate= 2010-05-30 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100614221343/http://www.sage.wisc.edu/riverdata/scripts/station_table.php?qual=32&filenum=2250 |archivedate= 2010-06-14 }}</ref>\n | basin_size        = {{convert|136628|km2|mi2}}<ref>{{cite web\n |url=http://earthtrends.wri.org/text/water-resources/map-398.html \n |title=Rio Grande de Santiago Watershed \n |publisher=World Resources Institute \u2013 EarthTrends \n |work=Watersheds of the World: North and Central America \n |year= 2006 \n |accessdate= 2010-05-30 \n |url-status=dead \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110611145336/http://earthtrends.wri.org/text/water-resources/map-398.html \n |archivedate= 2011-06-11 \n}}</ref>\n | river_system      =\n | tributaries_left  =\n | tributaries_right = [[R\u00edo Verde (Jalisco)|R\u00edo Verde]], [[Juchipila River]], [[Bola\u00f1os River]], [[Huaynamota River]], [[Mololoa River]]\n}}\n\nThe '''Grande de Santiago River''' ({{lang-es|R\u00edo Grande de Santiago}})<ref>{{GEOnet2|32FA882B96423774E0440003BA962ED3|R\u00edo Grande de Santiago (Approved - N}}, [[National Geospatial-Intelligence Agency|United States National Geospatial-Intelligence Agency]]</ref> is one of the longest rivers in [[Mexico]], measuring up {{Convert|433|km|mi|0|abbr=on}} long. The river begins at [[Lake Chapala]] and continues roughly north-west through the [[Sierra Madre Occidental]], receiving the [[Rio Verde (Jalisco)|Verde]], Juchipila, Bola\u00f1os, and other tributaries. At [[La Yesca]], the [[La Yesca Dam]] was completed in 2012 and the [[El Caj\u00f3n Dam (Mexico)|El Caj\u00f3n Dam]] was completed downstream in 2007. Below El Caj\u00f3n, the [[Aguamilpa Dam]] was completed in 1993, creating a reservoir covering a large part of the territory of the municipality of [[El Nayar]] in [[Nayarit]]. From Aguamilpa, the river descends to the coastal lowlands, passing by [[Santiago Ixcuintla]] and empties into the Pacific Ocean, {{Convert|16|km|mi|0|abbr=on}} northwest of [[San Blas, Nayarit|San Blas]], in Nayarit. The river is viewed by some sources as a continuation of the [[Lerma River]], which flows into Lake Chapala.\n\nMexico possesses a small percentage of the world's freshwater reserve, 0.1%. According to an article named ''Water use (and abuse) and its effects on the crater-lakes of Valle de Santiago, Mexico'' \u201cmost Mexican lakes are in an advanced state of desiccation or senescence, with volumes and surface area greatly reduced because of human activities\u201d.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Alcocer |first1=Javier |last2=Escobar |first2=Elva |last3=Lugo |first3=Alfonso |title=Water use (and abuse) and its effects on the crater-lakes of Valle de Santiago, Mexico |url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/229863242_Water_use_and_abuse_and_its_effects_on_the_crater-lakes_of_Valle_de_Santiago_Mexico |website=ResearchGate.net |accessdate=4 November 2018}}</ref> Some examples of these damaging activities are wood cutting, inflow diversion for agriculture, groundwater over extraction, pollution and eutrophication. Together Rio Lerma Santiago is a little over 600 miles long, but alone Rio Santiago is reported to be 269 miles long. It is an extension of the Lerma River, which at 466 miles long it is one of Mexico's longest rivers. The water begins in the Mexican Plateau in Mexico City. Then travels westward and goes through the Lerma River, and empties in Lake Chapala, near Guadalajara. From there the water flows southward through Rio Santiago and dissipates to the Pacific Ocean near San Blas, in Nayarit. The river passes by Ocotl\u00e1n, Poncitl\u00e1n, Atequiza, Atotonilquillo, Juanacatl\u00e1n, El Salto, Tonal\u00e1 among other places.<ref name=\"Impact\">{{Cite journal|last1=Gonz\u00e1lez |first1=Paulina Martinez |last2=Hern\u00e1ndez |first2=Eduardo |year=2009 |title=Impactos de la contaminaci\u00f3n del R\u00edo Santiago en el bienestar de los habitantes de El Salto, Jalisco / Impacts from Contamination of the Santiago River on the Well-being of the Inhabitants of El Salto, Jalisco  |journal=Espacio Abierto Cuaderno Venezolano de Sociolog\u00eda |volume=18 |issue=4 |pages=708\u2013729, page 711 |url=https://dialnet.unirioja.es/descarga/articulo/3211528.pdf }}</ref>\n\n==Pollution==\nLess than fifty years ago the river was a place to fish, bathe, and swim.{{Citation needed|date=August 2018}}  It is now a river full of pollutants. The Instituto Mexicano de Tecnolog\u00eda del Agua (IMTA) found over a thousand different chemicals in the main channel and its tributaries. These substances included semi-volatile and volatile organic compounds, such as [[phthalates]] (hormonal disruptors), [[phenol]]s (compounds that affect neuronal development), [[toluene]] (a [[neurotoxin]]), and [[carcinogenic]] flame retardants.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Enciso L. |first=Angelica |date=25 March 2013 |title=Muerte lenta del r\u00edo Santiago por contaminaci\u00f3n |newspaper=[[La Jornada]] |location=\tMexico City |url=http://www.jornada.com.mx/2013/03/25/politica/002n1pol |archive-url=https://archive.is/pLGHi?url=http://www.jornada.com.mx/2013/03/25/politica/002n1pol |archive-date=12 August 2018 |url-status=live |df=dmy}} ''citing'' the report [https://web.archive.org/web/20151231152641/http://hazalgo.org/descargas/estudio_completo_imta.zip \"Actualizaci\u00f3n del estudio de calidad del agua del r\u00edo Santiago\"]</ref>  This river is one of the most polluted in Mexico.{{Citation needed|date=August 2018}}\n\nIn February 2008 an eight-year-old boy, Miguel Angel Lopez Rocha, died after he fell into the river.<ref>{{harvnb|Gonz\u00e1lez|Hern\u00e1ndez|2009|page=713}}</ref> Rocha fell near the El Salto Falls. He died nineteen days later. His autopsy indicated heavy metal poison was the reason for his death. This brought attention to the severe contamination of the river. After this unfortunate incident the local community organized a group called \"Un Salto de Vida\" (\"A Leap for Life\"), which sponsored the second National Assembly on Environmental Impacts held in El Salto in May 2009.<ref name=\"Impact\" /><ref>Alcocer, Javier, Elva Escobar, and Alfonso Lugo. \"Water Use (And Abuse) and Its Effects on the Crater\u2010lakes of Valle De Santiago, Mexico.\" Lakes & Reservoirs: Research & Management, 5.3 (2000): 145-149.</ref><ref>G\u00f3mez-Balandra, Mar\u00eda Antonieta, Edmundo D\u00edaz-Pardo, and Altagracia Guti\u00e9rrez-Hern\u00e1ndez. \"Composici\u00f3n De La Comunidad \u00edctica De La Cuenca Del R\u00edo Santiago, M\u00e9xico, Durante Su Desarrollo Hidr\u00e1ulico Fish Community Composition of the Santiago River Basin, Mexico, During Its Hydraulic Development.\" Hidrobiol\u00f3gica, 22.1 (2012): 62-78.</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of longest rivers of Mexico]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://archive.is/20030724201338/http://www.iucn.org/themes/wani/eatlas/html/na20.html Water Resources  Atlas]\n{{Clear}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Rio Grande De Santiago}}\n[[Category:Rivers of Jalisco]]\n[[Category:Rivers of Nayarit]]\n\n[[de:R\u00edo Grande de Santiago]]\n", "text_old": "{{distinguish|Rio Grande}}\n{{no footnotes|date=September 2017}}\n{{expand Spanish|R\u00edo Grande de Santiago|date=July 2012}}\n{{Infobox river\n | name              = R\u00edo Grande de Santiago\n | image             = Rio Santiago.jpg\n | image_size        = 250px\n | image_caption     = Grande de Santiago River at the [[Nayarit]]\u2013[[Jalisco]] border\n | map               = Mexico rivers.jpg\n | map_size          = 250px\n | map_caption       = Major rivers of Mexico, with Grande de Santiago (labelled Rio Santiago) in west\u2013center\n | source1_location  = [[Lake Chapala]]\n | mouth_location    = [[Pacific Ocean]] at [[San Blas, Nayarit|San Blas]] / [[Santiago Ixcuintla]], [[Nayarit]]\n | subdivision_type1 = Country\n | subdivision_name1 = [[Mexico]]\n | progression       = \n | length            = {{Convert|433|km|mi|0|abbr=on}}\n | source1_elevation = \n | mouth_elevation   = \n | mouth_coordinates = {{coord|21|37|41|N|105|26|52|W|display=inline,title}}\n | discharge1_avg    = Average: {{convert|320|m3/s|cuft/s}}<br>Maximum: {{convert|2113|m3/s|cuft/s}}<br>Minimum: {{convert|29.5|m3/s|cuft/s}}<br><ref name=\"RDD\">{{cite web|url=http://www.sage.wisc.edu/riverdata/scripts/station_table.php?qual=32&filenum=2250 |title=Santiago Discharge near El Capomal |publisher=Center for Sustainability and the Global Environment |work=River Discharge Database |date= 1965\u20131981 |accessdate= 2010-05-30 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100614221343/http://www.sage.wisc.edu/riverdata/scripts/station_table.php?qual=32&filenum=2250 |archivedate= 2010-06-14 }}</ref>\n | basin_size        = {{convert|136628|km2|mi2}}<ref>{{cite web\n |url=http://earthtrends.wri.org/text/water-resources/map-398.html \n |title=Rio Grande de Santiago Watershed \n |publisher=World Resources Institute \u2013 EarthTrends \n |work=Watersheds of the World: North and Central America \n |year= 2006 \n |accessdate= 2010-05-30 \n |url-status=dead \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110611145336/http://earthtrends.wri.org/text/water-resources/map-398.html \n |archivedate= 2011-06-11 \n}}</ref>\n | river_system      =\n | tributaries_left  =\n | tributaries_right = [[R\u00edo Verde (Jalisco)|R\u00edo Verde]], [[Juchipila River]], [[Bola\u00f1os River]], [[Huaynamota River]], [[Mololoa River]]\n}}\n\nThe '''Grande de Santiago River''' ({{lang-es|R\u00edo Grande de Santiago}})<ref>{{GEOnet2|32FA882B96423774E0440003BA962ED3|R\u00edo Grande de Santiago (Approved - N}}, [[National Geospatial-Intelligence Agency|United States National Geospatial-Intelligence Agency]]</ref> is one of the longest rivers in [[Mexico]], measuring up {{Convert|433|km|mi|0|abbr=on}} long. The river begins at [[Lake Chapala]] and continues roughly north-west through the [[Sierra Madre Occidental]], receiving the [[Rio Verde (Jalisco)|Verde]], Juchipila, Bola\u00f1os, and other tributaries. At [[La Yesca]], the [[La Yesca Dam]] was completed in 2012 and the [[El Caj\u00f3n Dam (Mexico)|El Caj\u00f3n Dam]] was completed downstream in 2007. Below El Caj\u00f3n, the [[Aguamilpa Dam]] was completed in 1993, creating a reservoir covering a large part of the territory of the municipality of [[El Nayar]] in [[Nayarit]]. From Aguamilpa, the river descends to the coastal lowlands, passing by [[Santiago Ixcuintla]] and empties into the Pacific Ocean, {{Convert|16|km|mi|0|abbr=on}} northwest of [[San Blas, Nayarit|San Blas]], in Nayarit. The river is viewed by some sources as a continuation of the [[Lerma River]], which flows into Lake Chapala.\n\nMexico possesses a small percentage of the world\u2019s freshwater reserve, 0.1%. According to an article named ''Water use (and abuse) and its effects on the crater-lakes of Valle de Santiago, Mexico'' \u201cmost Mexican lakes are in an advanced state of desiccation or senescence, with volumes and surface area greatly reduced because of human activities\u201d.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Alcocer |first1=Javier |last2=Escobar |first2=Elva |last3=Lugo |first3=Alfonso |title=Water use (and abuse) and its effects on the crater-lakes of Valle de Santiago, Mexico |url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/229863242_Water_use_and_abuse_and_its_effects_on_the_crater-lakes_of_Valle_de_Santiago_Mexico |website=ResearchGate.net |accessdate=4 November 2018}}</ref> Some examples of these damaging activities are wood cutting, inflow diversion for agriculture, groundwater over extraction, pollution and eutrophication. Together Rio Lerma Santiago is a little over 600 miles long, but alone Rio Santiago is reported to be 269 miles long. It is an extension of the Lerma River, which at 466 miles long it is one of Mexico\u2019s longest rivers. The water begins in the Mexican Plateau in Mexico City. Then travels westward and goes through the Lerma River, and empties in Lake Chapala, near Guadalajara. From there the water flows southward through Rio Santiago and dissipates to the Pacific Ocean near San Blas, in Nayarit. The river passes by Ocotl\u00e1n, Poncitl\u00e1n, Atequiza, Atotonilquillo, Juanacatl\u00e1n, El Salto, Tonal\u00e1 among other places.<ref name=\"Impact\">{{Cite journal|last1=Gonz\u00e1lez |first1=Paulina Martinez |last2=Hern\u00e1ndez |first2=Eduardo |year=2009 |title=Impactos de la contaminaci\u00f3n del R\u00edo Santiago en el bienestar de los habitantes de El Salto, Jalisco / Impacts from Contamination of the Santiago River on the Well-being of the Inhabitants of El Salto, Jalisco  |journal=Espacio Abierto Cuaderno Venezolano de Sociolog\u00eda |volume=18 |issue=4 |pages=708\u2013729, page 711 |url=https://dialnet.unirioja.es/descarga/articulo/3211528.pdf }}</ref>  \n\n==Pollution==\nLess than fifty years ago the river was a place to fish, bathe, and swim.{{Citation needed|date=August 2018}}  It is now a river full of pollutants. The Instituto Mexicano de Tecnolog\u00eda del Agua (IMTA) found over a thousand different chemicals in the main channel and its tributaries. These substances included semi-volatile and volatile organic compounds, such as [[phthalates]] (hormonal disruptors), [[phenol]]s (compounds that affect neuronal development), [[toluene]] (a [[neurotoxin]]), and [[carcinogenic]] flame retardants.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Enciso L. |first=Angelica |date=25 March 2013 |title=Muerte lenta del r\u00edo Santiago por contaminaci\u00f3n |newspaper=[[La Jornada]] |location=\tMexico City |url=http://www.jornada.com.mx/2013/03/25/politica/002n1pol |archive-url=https://archive.is/pLGHi?url=http://www.jornada.com.mx/2013/03/25/politica/002n1pol |archive-date=12 August 2018 |url-status=live |df=dmy}} ''citing'' the report [https://web.archive.org/web/20151231152641/http://hazalgo.org/descargas/estudio_completo_imta.zip \"Actualizaci\u00f3n del estudio de calidad del agua del r\u00edo Santiago\"]</ref>  This river is one of the most polluted in Mexico.{{Citation needed|date=August 2018}} \n\nIn February 2008 an eight-year-old boy, Miguel Angel Lopez Rocha, died after he fell into the river.<ref>{{harvnb|Gonz\u00e1lez|Hern\u00e1ndez|2009|page=713}}</ref> Rocha fell near the El Salto Falls. He died nineteen days later. His autopsy indicated heavy metal poison was the reason for his death. This brought attention to the severe contamination of the river. After this unfortunate incident the local community organized a group called \"Un Salto de Vida\" (\"A Leap for Life\"), which sponsored the second National Assembly on Environmental Impacts held in El Salto in May 2009.<ref name=\"Impact\" /><ref>Alcocer, Javier, Elva Escobar, and Alfonso Lugo. \"Water Use (And Abuse) and Its Effects on the Crater\u2010lakes of Valle De Santiago, Mexico.\" Lakes & Reservoirs: Research & Management, 5.3 (2000): 145-149.</ref><ref>G\u00f3mez-Balandra, Mar\u00eda Antonieta, Edmundo D\u00edaz-Pardo, and Altagracia Guti\u00e9rrez-Hern\u00e1ndez. \"Composici\u00f3n De La Comunidad \u00edctica De La Cuenca Del R\u00edo Santiago, M\u00e9xico, Durante Su Desarrollo Hidr\u00e1ulico Fish Community Composition of the Santiago River Basin, Mexico, During Its Hydraulic Development.\" Hidrobiol\u00f3gica, 22.1 (2012): 62-78.</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of longest rivers of Mexico]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://archive.is/20030724201338/http://www.iucn.org/themes/wani/eatlas/html/na20.html Water Resources  Atlas]\n{{Clear}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Rio Grande De Santiago}}\n[[Category:Rivers of Jalisco]]\n[[Category:Rivers of Nayarit]]\n\n[[de:R\u00edo Grande de Santiago]]\n", "name_user": "I dream of horses", "label": "safe", "comment": "clean up,typo(s) fixed: \u2019s \u2192 's (2)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Grande_de_Santiago_River"}
